{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_grasso_ver02/data/sn82014085/00393347387/1938031801/0280.xml":{"full_text":"School Children to Demonstrate Latest Safety Methods\nTeachers to Cooperate\nAt Highway Session\nIn New Haven, April 4\nPractical Instructions to Be Given When Educational\nLeaders Meet in Effort to Reduce Accidents\nin Connecticut\nActual methods and means, of in\nstruction for safer participation by\nschool children in traffic will be\noutlined by school teachers and of\nicials and demonstrated with the\nassistance of school pupils at the\neducation group meeting program\nas a part of the highway safety\nconference In New Haven, Monday,\nApril 4.\nCompletion of final arrangements\nfor the meeting, which will include\nan address by Dr. Ernest W. Butter\nfield, Commissioner of Education,\nand a welcome to the delegates by\nRobert I. Catlin, vice chairman of\nthe highway safety commission, has\nbeen announced by Robert C. Dem\ning, supervisor of adult education\nfor the state department of educa\ntion, who will preside at this two\nhour afternoon session of the all\nday conference.\nEducational Phases\nThe program has been designed\nto give teacher delegates, and of\nficials concerned primarily with the\neducational phases of highway\nsafety, Information on progress in\nsafety Instruction in educational in\nstructions In Connecticut and other\nstates. A talk on his experiences in\n\u2018\u2018Getting the Highway Safety Pro\ngram Underway\u201d by Dr. Herbert J.\nStack, director, educational divi\nsion, national conservation bureau,\nwill conclude the meeting.\nA varied program will Include ex\nMAPLE SAPlS\nRUNNING NOW\nBumper Crop Reported in\nVermont\u2014Weather\nIs Watched\nBt. Jonnsbury, vt., March 18\u2014\ni UP)\u2014Maple sugar \"farmers\u201d have\nbegun harvesting the 1938 crop\nwhich is expected to be a bumper\none because of ideal weather con\nditions.\nThough only 20 per cent of the\ntrees havd been tapped, the harvest\ning is expected to be in full swing\nwithin a week. Sap has been run\nning for more than a week in the\nsouthern section of the state.\nThin columns of smoke already\nare curling over the upland sugar\nbush. Sap-gatherers are hustling\nfrom tree to tree, and horse-hauled\nsleds bearing vast vats are winding\nover snow-covered woodland trails.\nThe sap. which looks and tastes\nlike sweetened water, drips from\nmetal or hickory spouts inserted in\nholes bored in the south or east side\nof trees. Though an old wooden\nbucket occasionally is seen, small\npipe lines usually deliver the sap to\nthe evaporators free of twigs and\nbark.\nA barrel of sap, 32 gallons, boils\ndown to one gallon of syrup. One\ngallon of syrup can be made into\neight pounds of sugar. This state\nproduces one-third of the nation\u2019s\nmaple sugar and syrup.\nBecause of recent rain night\nfreezes and warm days, conditions\nare favorable for a bumper crop this\nyear. However, the size of the crop\nwill depend on the fickleness of the\nweather. A period of continued\nwarm, dry weather would have an\nadverse effect.\nMore than 700.000 acres of United\nStates public land were added to\nthe Navajo Indian reservation in\nUtah, to settle a 20-year contro\nversy.\nplanation of the Junior Traffic\nCommission movement by Miss Ada\nV. Hallock and Mildred Walsh, one\nof her pupils at Central High\nschool, Bridgeport, and a panel dis\ncussion among pupils of six high\nschools led by John A. Young, as\nsistant superintendent of schools in\nBridgeport.\nFollowing a presentation on the\nprogram of safety instruction by\nDr. Charles J. Prohaska, supervisor\nof health and safety education for\nthe state department of education,\nthe two general methods of in\nstruction in Connecticut schools will\nbe demonstrated by two instructors\nof the New Haven High school.\nDemonstration of the \u201ccase study\nmethod\" will be conducted by Miss\nJ. Edna Johnson, while the \u201cin\ntegration method\u201d will be demon\nstrated by Miss Leone Brandon,\nboth teachers at the New Haven\nHigh school.\nPanel Discussion\nPupil participants in the panel\ndiscussion on \u201cThe Contribution of\nBy School to the Safety Movement,\"\nled by Superintendent Young; will\nbe Irene Buckley, Bassick High\nschool, Bridgeport; Mildred Lindon,\nStratford High school; Gail Smith,\nRoger Ludlow High school, Fair\nfield; Frank Sladky, state trade\nschool, Bridgeport; Charles Wilcox,\nCentral High school, Bridgeport;\nand Ethel Saska, Warren Harding\nHigh school, Bridgeport.\nAll these boys and girls are mem\nbers of the Bridgeport Junior\nTraffic Commission, the first such\norganization in the country, brought\ninto action through the initiative\nand interest of the younger genera\ntion in the traffic problem.\nSEVERAL SCOUTS\nWIN PROMOTIONS\nSt. John\u2019s Church Troop\nHost at Board of Review\nMeeting Thursday\nEmil Detlefsen, Jr., of Troop 10,\nof the First Lutheran church, was\nadvanced to a second class rank at\nthe district \u201cD\u201d board or review\nheld last evening at St. John's Par\nish House under supervision of Wal\nter P. Green, representing Matta\ntuck Council Committee on Scout\nadvancement, Commisisoner Harry\nS. Hyde and Assistant Scout Execu\ntive Henry Donahue.\nTroop 1 of that parish was host\ntroop.\nOther scout awards were made as\nfollows: Benjamin Bradley, Troop\n1, St. John\u2019s church, Joseph Delaney,\nTroop 4, St. Thomas church, Roger\nCarroll, Troop 10, First Lutheran\nchurch, and Robert Wooding, Troop\n19, South Federated church, all ad\nvanced to first class rank: Edward\nSprano, Troop 1, St. John\u2019s church,\nadvanced to star Scout rank; Ed\nward Fagan, Troop 4, St. Thomas\nchurch, merit badges in bookbind\ning and handicraft; Joseph Frisbie,\nTroop 4, merit badge in carpentry;\nWilliam Frisbie, Troop 4, merit\nbadges in Athletics and civics; Wil\nliam Tobin, Troop 9, St. Thomas\nchurch, merit badges in pathfind\ning, photography, public health;\nJames Ryan, Troop 9, merit badges\nIn pathfinding, public health and\nreading; and Roger Carroll, Troop\n10, First Lutheran church, merit\n[badge in bookbinding.\nHTABL1SHID 1885\nMisses' London Made\nBritish Coats in Galashiels\nScotch Fabrics\n$29.75\nAs thrillingly exciting as a girl's\nfirst cruise\u2014as rich and rare in\nfabrics, color tones, patterns, and\nhand needling as sunrise on the\nSussex Downs.\nThese are wonderful coats for\ncruise, travel and business wear\n\u2014\u25a0particularly fine for school\nteachers and business girls who\nhave to weather the vagaries of\nspring weather.\nIn a color range from pastel\nshades to plain color tones\u2014\nfrom Bantry checks to invisible\nplaids.\nBoy Finds Fiction Gun-Trap Really Works\nFascinated by a home-made gun trap described in a detective story, Delmar Morris, 16-year-old Harrison\nville, Mo., farm boy, shown above left, decided to find out if the thing would actually work. Police said that\nwhile Hugo Theden, a neighbor, was away from home, Deimar rigged the contraption, shown at the right,\nin Theden\u2019s kitchen. The string led from the trigger to the door, and Theden was seriously wounded when he\nentered. Delmar, who told police he had no grudge against the neighbor, hut simply wanted to try the thing\nout, is pictured reading another detective story while he awaits trial on assault to kill charges.\nDORIC CHAPTER\nCHURCH GUESTS\nDeMolays to Observe Ob=\nligatory Sunday; Vos=\nburgh Club Speaker\nMembers of Doric Chapter, Order\nof DeMolay, will observe obligatory\nSunday by attending the Second\nCongregational Church services next\nSunday morning. The following of\nficers will be in charge of the group:\nadvisor, Walter A. Smethurst; mas\nter councillor, Walter Forest: senior\ncouncillor, Harry Normand; and\njunior councillor, Elly Davenport.\nHarry C. Post, chairman of the\nevery member canvass committee of\nthe church, will preside at a meet\ning of generals, majors and staff\nworkers Sunday morning directly\nfollowing the service. It is hoped the\ncanvass will be entirely completed\nnext week.\nWilliam M. Vosburgh, Jr., mem\nber of the Sunday Republican edi\ntorial staff, will review the book,\n'\u2018Collectivism\u201d by William H. Cham\nberlain at the Sunday Noon club\nnext Sunday at 12 o'clock in the\nchapel. This book is a contrast of\ndemocracy with communism and\nfascism. The author spent twelve\nyears in Russia and three in the Far\nEast as correspondent of the \"Chris\ntian Science Monitor.\u201d\nAubrey Hills, algebra teacher at\nCrosby high, will speak on \u201cLife in\nPorto Rico\u201d and show pictures at\nthe Pilgrim Fellowship meeting\nSunday afternoon at 5 o\u2019clock in the\nchapel. Mr. Hills was principal of\nSan Juan high school for three\nyears.\n\u2018FAULTY TAXES\u2019\nARE CENSORED\nBusiness Leaders Seek\nRevision in Administra*\ntion Bill\nWashington, March 18.\u2014(UP)\u2014\nBusiness leaders today blamed\n\u201cfaulty and oppressive taxes\" for\nthe current business recession and\nasked the senate finance commit\ntee to change the administration\u2019s\ntax revision bill.\nContinuing attacks against al\nleged inequities of the undistributed\nprofits and capital gains taxes, they\nurged broadening the tax base to\ncreate increased tax-consciousness\nin the face of continued heavy gov\nernment spending.\n\u201cIn the opinion of many people,\u201d\nM. L. Seidman of the New York\nboard of trade said, \u201cwe are not in\na business recession. We are in a\ndepression, a synthetic depression,\na managed economy depression, a\ndepression that is estimated to have\ncost us some $70,000,000,000 in the\nperiod of a single year.\n\u201cMany of our troubles can be\ntraced directly to faulty and op\npressive taxes.\n\u201cTaxation is undoubtedly the most\ndecisive deflationary influence in\nour capital economy today. It would\nseem to use that the best invest\nment congress can make in reliev\ning the present distress to business\nand employment, Is to take a con\nstructive, long-term view of our tax\ning methods.\"\n\u201cA reasonable tax policy, one\nwhich will allow business to carry\non and prosper, must eventually\nproduce greater revenue than a sys\ntem of punitive and extreme tax\nation.\u201d\nSeidman said the house-approved\nbill is \u201cstill a long way from what\nis needed to get business back on its\nfeet.\u201d\nGALES STRIKE\nNEAR BOSTON\nBoston, March 18.\u2014(UP)\u2014Water\nfront residents today surveyed dam\nage wrought by flood tides lashed\nby a 50-mlle gale.\nHardest hit were the Post Island,\nAdams Shore, Bethel Beach, Rock\nIsland and Clllows sections of\nQuincy. Nearly 150 homes were\nflooded.\nSurf and spray whipped across\nboulevards and shattered windows at\nNantasket Beach and Wlnthrop.\nIn Boston yesterday the rainfall\ntotaled .99 of an inch.\nIntermittent light rain was pre\ndicted for today with tomorrow fair\nand warmer.\nLithuania has the lowest cost of\nliving figure of any nation In the\nworld. Its costs dropped 55 per cent\nas compared with 1929.\nFraternal News\nMattatuck Council\nMattatuck council, Royal Ar\ncanum, will hold an entertain\nment and dance at Mechanics hall\nMonday night in celebration of\nthe council's 56th anniversary. A\nbusiness meeting will bo held at\nmf\u20147T.V.T \"''\u2019Wr'VZPMm\nWILLIAM J. BRIGGS\nCommitteeman\n7 o\u2019clock, with the anniversary\ncelebration scheduled to start at\n8:15.\nWilliam J. Briggs Is chairman\nof the committee in charge. Other\nmembers are Regent Michael\nRyan; Secretary Wallace Roberts;\nOrator Louis DiLco and Joseph\nJacovino.\nHarmony Lodge\nMembers form the French small\ntube branch of the American\nBrass Co., worked the master ma\nson degree at a meeting of Har\nmony lodge, A. F. A. M. at Ma\nsonic temple last night. A social\nfollowed the meeting, with enter\ntainment and refreshments being\nenjoyed.\nBrass City Aerie\nFour candidates were initiated\nand applications of four other\ncandidates were accepted at last\nnight's meeting of Brass City\nAerie of Eagles, a St. Patrick\u2019s\nday celebration was also held.\nSpeakers included Dr. George\nLeonard. John E. Graham and\nDennis R. Mitchell, treasurer, who\nexpressed a belief that a large\nclass will be initiated April 21. At\nthat time a formal celebration\nwill be held in honor of the third\nanniversary of the passage of the\nold age pension act, first spon\nsored by the Eagles. State Secre\ntary Moran will be the speaker.\nEntertainment was offered by\nLouis Denegiss, Thomas Moran\nand Bill Karmen. Refreshments\nwere served.\nPine Rock\nPine Rock Circle, Lady Forest\ners, will meet tonight at Mech\nanics hall. A social program has\nbeen arranged. Members will dis\ncuss plans for spring activities.\nMayflower Camp\nMembers of Mayflower camp\nlast night celebrated the 43d an\nniversary of the Royal Neighbors\nof America. Guests from several\nother cities in the state were\npresent.\nAn entertainment and social fol\nlowed the anniversary program.\nIt was announced that the camp\nwill be host at a district meeting\nto be held May 21 at Speedwell\nhall.\nCanton Martin\nMembers of Canton T. R. Mar\ntin will go to Bridgeport April 7\nto attend a meeting at which the\nPatriarchal degree will be worked\non a large class of candidates.\nThe regular meeting of the local\norganization scheduled for that\nnight will open at 7 o'clock so\nthat members will have time to\nreach Bridgeport for the cere\nmonies.\nClan McAlpine\nDavid Gowans was chosen chief\nof Clan McAlphine, Order of Scot\ntish Clan, last night at the an\nnual meeting at Foresters\u2019 hall and\nhe, with the other officers, will be\ninstalled April 21. A social pro\ngram by members of Lady Mc\nAlpine Lodge was held following\nthe meeting.\nOther officers elected were: Tan\nist, William Watt; recording secre\ntary, John Brown; treasurer, Alex\nander Galbraith; chaplain, David\nCraig; senior henchman, James\nWilson; seneschal, Peter Emer\nson; warder, James Gardner; sen\ntinel, Andrew Wylie; \"Courier\u201d\ncorrespondent, Donald Macintosh;\nstandard bearer, Mr. Wylie, Mr.\nGardner and George Cruick\nslianks; trustees, John Steves, John\nCurrie, William Carew; auditors,\nThomas Turner, John Stevens and\nRobert Gardner.\nBUTTER BOYCOTT\nIN TORONTO, CAN,\nToronto, Ont., March 18.\u2014(UP).\n\u2014Members of the Toroto House\nwives' union, organized to reduce\nfood priest, asserted today that\ntheir \u201cboycott butter week\" would\nbe observed by a majority of the\ncity's housewives.\nThe boycott will start Monday\nand end March 26. The purpose, ac\ncording to Mrs. Bertha Lamb, presi\ndent. and organizer of the union, is\nto reduce the butter price from\n40 cents a pound \u201cto 30 cents or\nless.\u201d\nPremier Mitchell F. Hepburn.\nMayor Ralph Day and members of\nthe Ontario Legislature will be in\nformed of the boycott and its pur\npose. The union will ask Hepburn\nto roder a legislative investigation\nof commodity prices\nHE\u2019S THANKFUL FOR \u2019HOPPERS\nTimber Lake, S. D.\u2014(UP)\u2014 At\nleast one farmer is thankful for\ngrasshoppers. Alfred Kleiner is a\nturkey raiser and he says that since\nthe \u2019hoppers have routed themselves\nthrough hts land he has \u201cthe cheap\nest turkey feed\u201d he has ever seen.\nOPEN TONIGHT\nUntil 9 P. M.\nManufacturers Sale\nOF\nSALANTI AND BERTINI\nPiano Accordions\nFREE 20 PRIVATE LESSONS\nWITH 24 BASS AT $59.50\nFREE 25 PRIVATE LESSONS\nWITH 48 BASS AT $119.50\nFREE 40 PRIVATE LESSONS\nWITH 120 BASS AT $159.50\nTeachers Ike Dervis and Lewis Di Negris\nCome in today or tonight sure.\nam\nnrs\nINC.158Grand St\nTHE HOUSE OF MUSIC\nLEGION GROUPS\nTO HOLD PARTY\nCorporal Coyle Post and\nAuxiliary Plan Card\nGames Tomorrow\nMembers of Corp. Coyle Post No.\n1, American Legion, and its auxil\niary will celebrate the 19th anni\nversary of the formation of the\nAmerican Legion with a party aL\nthe Legion home on Holmes avenue\ntomorrow night. Pasts all over the\ncountry tomorrow will hold celebra\ntions.\nThe post will entertain members\nof the auxiliary tomorrow night\nwith a varied program. Motion pic\ntures will be shown, bridge and oth\ner card games will be played, enter\ntainment presented and refresh\nments served.\nA coast to coast broadcast a few\ndays ago was given in honor of the\nanniversary. Noted Legionnaires\nwere among the speakers.\nPlans for tomorrow night's anni\nversary celebration are in charge of\na committee which includes Junior\nCommander George Kamofsky, Ad\njutant Joseph Brenneis, Paul Staf\nstrom, Jay Connellan, Raymond\nWalker, Chet Haude, Victor Baker\nand John Wall.\nPlans for the auxiliary\u2019s partici\npation in the celebration are in\ncharge of Mrs. Mae Birt, president.\nEVA VOLAGE FILES\nDIVORCE PETITION\nPetition for divorce was Hied in\nsuperior court today by Eva Viltra\nkis Volage against Francis Volage.\nCustody of a minor child is also\nasked.\nThe petitioner was married to the\ndefendant, Nov. 26, 1933. She al\nleges cruelty.\nSaved Her Baby\nby Using Teeth\nmmmm mk mmmem\nWhen 2-year-old John Shaon\nfell into a 25-foot well at his\nhome near Fulton, Mo., his\nmother, Mrs. James Shaon, 22,\nshown above with the boy, jumped\nright in after him. The leap dis\nabled her arm, so she used her\nteeth to hold the youngster above\nthe water line until rescuers ar\nrived. They are pictured stand\ning on the well covering. Neither\nwas seriously hurt.\nWIFE CHANGES\nDIVORCE CUII*\nLoses Contest on Cruelty\nCharge, Now Files De=\nsertion Complaint\nBarred by Judge Edwin C. Dick-'*\nenson from receiving a divorce from\nher husband on grounds of intoier\nI able cruelty, Emma Hozebin Me-\nI Bride of this city today asked Judged.\nPrank P. McEvoy to grant her the\nI decree on grounds of desertion.\nJudge McEvoy reserved decision\nafter hearing the uncontested action,\ntoday.\nThe plaintiff claims that her hus\nband, Ignatius McBride, of Litch\nfield deserted her in August, 1934,\nThey were married at Patterson,\nNew Jersey, September 1, 1932.\nIn her previous action, tried here\nlast year before Judge Dickenson,;\nthe woman claimed intolerable.,,\ncruelty, in that she had to work\nlong hours each day on her lius\nband\u2019s farm and he never treated\nher cordially. Judge Dickenson de\nnied the divorce commenting that;\nwhen she married a farmer she na\nturally assumed a life of hard work.\nJudge McEvoy also reserved de\ncision today after hearing the evi\ndence in the action of Effle H. Luke\nagainst John J. Luke. Cruelty was\nalleged. They were married June 7,\n1934.\nThe case of Olive J. Roden\nagainst Arthur C. Roden was placed\non the uncontested list.\nDecision was reserved in the ap\nplication of Sadie Partridge Bar\ntholomew to have William Barthol\nomew declared in contempt of court\nfor failure to pay an alimony order.\nThere are about 75 different types\nof meteorites. They are divided in\nto three main classes: stony meteor\nites or aerolites, iron meteorites or\nsiderites, and stony-irons or sldero\nlites.\nNO INTEREST\nOR CARRYING CHARGES\n53 PIECE\nDINNER\nSET\nService For 8\n$fV95\n50c DOWN\n50c A WEEK\nA smartly styled, yet con\nservative design on a tinted\nbackground makes this din\nnerware really beautiful. High\nquality china, with dense and\nsturdy body. The service in\ncludes meat platter and vege\ntable dish.\n15 EAST MAIN ST.\nOPEN AN ACCOUNT\nLook Pretty, Please...\nin this New Group of\nCharmingly Wearable\nSpring Hats\n$1.98\nImportant types, every one, in a refresh\ning straw or felt that\u2019s perfect for the\napproach to spring and a price that\nbudget-watchers will leap at. Pick your\ntype\u2014sailor, Breton, bonnet, pillbox,\nbumper or nautical off-the-facer, flying\nribbons or abloom with flower bouquets.\nHAT SHOP MAIN FLOOR\nINVITE YOU TO OPEN A LORRAINE CHARGE ACCOUNT\nUEAMftiUAI\n'iVVi","height":"28228","width":"20644"}}
